<br>
Now, my other point is that for a QUEST to be considered epic, what do you think of in non-EQ terms?  A quest that takes a long time to complete, with many sub-adventures along the way that need to be done to complete it.  Now, where are the sub-adventures/quests?  We get a shopping list of items for most of them, hand them in, and it's over.  Difficulty isn't the key, it's the improper use of the term epic that I find fault with.<br>
<br>
Now, a rebuild of the wizard epic quest with this in mind.  Note that long-term, it's the same effect:<br>
<br>
From Camin:  The one that has knowledge, Arantir was last seen traveling northward into the snowy wastes.<br>
<br>
On traveling, and asking every NPC around, you find one that says, &quot;I know of him, but he has chosen not to reveal himself to just anyone.  Ask for Arantir in the City of Halas, and perhaps he will make himself known to you in time&quot;.<br>
<br>
From there, you come, and are told to deliver several potions for the vendor/NPC to different NPCs around Halas, and a final delivery to be made to Camin.   It is then that we get the next part, that Arantir reveals himself.  You do the bit with the ring to Felwithe, return, and then he tells you about each staff.  Now, instead of the staff being where it is currently, you have several sub-quests/plots....<br>
<br>
From Venril Sathir, he no longer has it, one of his followers has stolen it, and all you find is a diary entry that indicates who the thief was, and a mention of where the thief might have gone.  You track down the thief, through multiple battles and in a battle with a mob that has that 125k HP, you finally get the staff.<br>
<br>
<br>
This sort of idea, that you need to go through many steps to even get one staff out of three would make it more epic, and by having more steps, it also allows for less of a bottleneck on each step.  <br>
<br>
My idea is that it shouldn't be this, &quot;Get me 3 items and bring them back&quot;, and having those three items be difficult because of rare spawns and rare drops off rare spawns.  They should be long and drawn out(the way this post turned out to be).  They should make it so each PIECE feels like you had to spend a lot of time, not GUESSING where to go, but actually going through the steps needed.  Figure 15 steps per staff to get.  You will feel like the Gnarled Staff, when you finally get it, is a great achievement.  Useful on it's own(as it is now), but all the more rare because it's a pain to get.  Unlike the magician epic quest, there should be NOTHING that requires you go that deep into a very unused and expensive to raid zone.  But that's another argument.  <br>
<br>
Difficulty is not the thing I disagree with you on, it's what you consider epic, and it's clear Verant has no clue.<br>
